Mediocre at best. In fact I think this game is an exercise in mediocrity. Everything from the graphics to the gameplay, sound, writing etc. is unpolished and many a times laughable. The controls don't help either. Why on earth would you not have controller support for this? And don't even get me started on the retarded IAP model. You want to charge a decent sum for playing the game and follow it up with stupid in-app purchases? That explains why you don't have controller support, because the only reason why people would want to purchase your health potions is because the touch controls are retarded and tend to get non-responsive.

I am saddened by the fact that I had to turn the game off in order to write this review. And just to mention, I wasn't asked to do it (by the game), I'm writing on my own accord simply because I am amazed! This game is worth every penny as far as I'm concerned. Absolutely love it! Graphics are great, I love the story line, everything runs smoothly... Sometimes in games like this one, I have a problem with the camera, it turns too fast when you move it around etc (and yes I know you can adjust it in the settings most of the time) but this one didn't require me to touch and change anything, it is perfect as is. I genuinely like most of the Gameloft games but this one is by far my favourite. I just wonder how is it that I haven't found it earlier? 🌟🌟🌟🌟🌟

While it lasted anyway - felt once you get the hang of how the game mechanics work, it's pretty easy to work out a strategy for each type of enemy -and if you can't resist the urge to use the same strategy as learned in the 1st half of the game, then the 2nd half is really just a walk in the park. Too easy by far. However, the game play is spot on and fighting styles combined with spells make it seem more complicated than it really is. The graphics are brilliant for a game this old (on par with hack n slash releases recently -May 2015)Difficulty is okay but as I said when you get th hang of it the last half of the game will seem too easy and you might feel let down by this. Gorgeous arenas and nice spell effects round off what is a pretty awesome game... Definitely feel a need for a sequel. 5 stars.

I've played a lot of Gameloft games over the year and have mixed results. Maybe its the large quantity of games they push, for starters. As a result I've never really liked Gameloft games, whereas I've so desperately wanted to. Most of them are clones of cult favorites but that doesn't matter to me. Usually though, the controls are bad, graphics are horrible, and the games chock full of bugs. Not the case with Wild Blood. This game is fun, challenging, and graphically stunning. It's built on the Unreal Engine so you get these cutting edge graphics you would never expect from Gameloft. The storyline is not bad at all, it's based on medieval time and has all the cheesy themes you'd want from a game like that :). The game plays pretty smooth although there are some parts that will be unresponsive, mainly just unlocking a treasure chest puzzle. I enjoy the default camera view but sometimes it can mess up quite bad. I wish there was more advanced notice on when boss battles come, although this does make the game extra challenging. All in all, I'm very satisfied. 5/5 on this one, keep up the good work!

I can understand that some may find $7.99 overpriced, but I found it on sale for $0.99, and that is quite a bargain. There is an option to pay for in-game gold for potions or upgrades for weapons and armor, but you acquire enough gold in the game to get by.  Some have complained about paying 2000 gold to continue after losing to a boss. I have never needed to do so, as there is an abundance of save points, usually just before any boss fight. (Proper use of dodging usually keeps you alive through boss fights anyway.)  The graphics are excellent, the story entertaining, and I was generally impressed with the game. Five stars well earned.

I used to have an iPod touch. That's what I used for mobile gaming. I was enamored with Gameloft during that time. Their games were such high quality, and extremely fun to play. A few months ago, I purchased a Nexus 7 which is a HUGE upgrade in terms of gaming power. Unfortunately, I have been disappointed again and again by Gameloft since making the switch. It seems like every single Gameloft game is an iOS port, and suffers greatly in one way or another. Some games have great graphics, but suffer immensely in frame rate (looking at you, Asphalt 7 and NOVA 3) and some games just cut back severely in the graphics department to make framerates stable. This is the case with Wild Blood. My girlfriend and I both purchased the game during the 99 cent sale. I played it on her iPad 2, and then played it on my Nexus 7. The difference is night and day. The N7 version has NO enhanced effects. There is no motion blur when swinging the sword, the environment effects are lessened, and the textures are noticeably muddier. I want to be a Gameloft fanboy, I really do... But it's very hard when they keep putting out subpar efforts like this one.

The graphics are great. And that's the ONLY GOOD THING about this game. For a game of this high price, the package is not worth it. The game is VERY short (you can finish it in 1,5-2 hours), it runs choppy a lot of times (regardless of device, at least it's been tested on Xperia T and Samsung Galaxy S3), inconsistent controls aggravated again by choppiness, by far longest lasting loading screen of ANY game I've played in the last few years, and WORST OF ALL, the game gets difficult REALLY fast, which borderline FORCES you to buy (with REAL money) upgrades. The upgrade costs run from 2 to 80 (that's right, 80!!) euros, which is retarded considering you can buy a goddamn PS3 game for 60 euros, and in order to get your character to a DECENT level you need at least to buy the 5 euro upgrade.   The story is very thin, with poor voice acting, and the combat itself is extremely repetitive. It's basically a button masher (no real combos), and the combat plays exactly the same with all weapons besides the bow, which is only useful in some context-specific areas in this really short game.  Looking for an action-rpg? Bard's Tale is cheaper, about 6h long, and way better in all aspects.
